{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti chapter 11 in this corpus (the only version available, labeled as by an \"unknown\" author) is a short text of just six verses (206 words). It prescribes rules for giving gifts and food to deserving Brahmins, snātakas (bath-graduates), and Vedic scholars, such as during sacrifices or times of need.[^1][^2] There is no mention of killing animals, cats (*mārjāra* in Sanskrit), or related expiations (*prāyaścitta* or penances).**\n\nCorpus-wide searches for terms like \"cat\", \"kill\", \"killing a cat\", \"mārjāra\", \"animal\", and combinations with \"expiation\" or \"penance\" yielded no relevant results in Manusmṛti or any other work.[^3]\n\nTraditional editions of Manusmṛti chapter 11 (much longer, ~268 verses) do cover penances for killing various animals, but this specific passage (or the full chapter) is not present here. The Falsafa corpus contains only selected philosophical texts; this topic is not covered.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 11 (full chapter), [translation](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 11, [p-7d3e17](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/#p-7d3e17) to [p-259c16](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/#p-259c16).\n[^3]: No matching snippets from *search_corpus* across translation bodies.",
